1️⃣ If I do NOT use a landing zone, what risks happen?
Your answer

Then there will be no rule in the business infrastructure. Anyone can do whatever he/she wants, and security, cost or company policy might get affected.

Evaluation

✅ Correct idea
⚠️ Too generic

Better structured answer

If an organization does not implement a landing zone:

No governance

No policies enforcing tagging, region restrictions, or security rules.

Security risks

Resources may be publicly exposed.

No centralized identity or access control.

Cost sprawl

Teams deploy expensive resources without oversight.

Lack of standardization

Each team builds infrastructure differently.

Operational chaos

Logging, monitoring, and security auditing become inconsistent.

✔ Landing zones prevent these problems by enforcing standard governance and architecture before workloads are deployed.

2️⃣ Why should the platform team control networking instead of the app team?
Your answer

Because app team responsibility is to deploy app code, works on workload layer. It's not his responsibility to control things on platform level layer.

Evaluation

✅ Correct concept
⚠️ Missing security and architecture reasoning

Stronger answer

Networking should be managed by the platform team because:

Security consistency

Central control of firewalls, routing, and segmentation.

Architecture standardization

Ensures all workloads follow the same network design (e.g., hub-spoke).

Reduced risk

Application teams cannot accidentally expose services publicly.

Separation of duties

Platform team manages infrastructure; application teams manage applications.

Scalability

A centralized network architecture supports many applications without redesign.

3️⃣ What are 5 characteristics of a production-ready cloud environment?
Your answer

secured, governance ready, sku restrictions, tag enforcement, monitored

Evaluation

⚠️ Mostly correct but a bit narrow.

SKU restrictions and tag enforcement are actually governance tools, not separate characteristics.

A stronger 5 would be:

1️⃣ Governed

Policies enforce standards (tagging, allowed regions, resource restrictions)

2️⃣ Secure

Least privilege access, private networking, security monitoring

3️⃣ Observable

Centralized logging, monitoring, alerts, audit trails

4️⃣ Cost controlled

Budgets, tagging, cost analysis, SKU restrictions

5️⃣ Automated

Infrastructure deployed via IaC and CI/CD pipelines

These are the pillars of production environments.

4️⃣ If I scale to 50 applications, how does landing zone help?
Your answer

we dont have to set security, goverence, sky restriction, tag enforcement, add monitoring, audit things, plan for self recoverable. All this will be done on landing zone.

Evaluation

✅ Correct idea
⚠️ Needs clearer explanation

Stronger answer

A landing zone enables scaling to many applications by providing pre-configured governance and infrastructure.

Instead of configuring security, networking, monitoring, and policies for every application individually, those controls are defined once at the platform level.

When new applications are deployed:

They inherit policies

They inherit network design

They inherit monitoring and logging

They follow the same security and cost controls

This allows organizations to scale from a few applications to dozens or hundreds without redesigning the infrastructure each time.
